"{\"uid\": \"wired.com-story-how-the-car-free-los-angeles-olympics-will-work\", \"entities\": [{\"sentence\": \"THIS ARTICLE ISrepublished fromThe Conversationunder aCreative Commons license.\", \"from\": 0, \"to\": 79, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"With the Olympic torchextinguished in Paris, all eyes are turning toLos Angeles for the 2028 Olympics.\", \"from\": 81, \"to\": 183, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 119, \"end\": 124, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 0.9999999999995453, \"rank\": 4.747418523319758e-13, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The host city has promised that the next Summer Games will be \\\"car-free.\\\"\", \"from\": 185, \"to\": 258, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"For people who know Los Angeles, this seems overly optimistic.\", \"from\": 260, \"to\": 322, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 280, \"end\": 291, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Thecar remains kingin LA, despite growing public transit options.\", \"from\": 323, \"to\": 388, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"When LA hosted the Games in 1932, it hadan extensive public transportation system, with buses and anextensive network of electric streetcars.\", \"from\": 390, \"to\": 531, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Today, the trolleys are long gone; riders say city busesdon't come on schedule, and bus stops are dirty.\", \"from\": 532, \"to\": 636, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"What happened?\", \"from\": 637, \"to\": 651, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"This question fascinates me because I am abusiness professorwho studies why society abandons and then sometimes returns to certain technologies, such asvinyl records,landline phones, andmetal coins.\", \"from\": 653, \"to\": 851, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The demise of electric streetcars in Los Angeles and attempts to bring them back today vividly demonstrate the costs and challenges of such revivals.\", \"from\": 852, \"to\": 1001, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 889, \"end\": 900, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The 2028 Olympic Games will be held in existing sports venues around Los Angeles and are expected to host 15,000 athletes and over 1 million spectators.\", \"from\": 1003, \"to\": 1155, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1072, \"end\": 1083, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Transportation is a critical priority in any city, but especially so in Los Angeles, which has been a sprawling metropolis from the start.\", \"from\": 1157, \"to\": 1295, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1229, \"end\": 1240, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the early 1900s, railroad magnateHenry Huntington, who owned vast tracts of land around LA, started subdividing his holdings into small plots and building homes.\", \"from\": 1297, \"to\": 1461, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1339, \"end\": 1349, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Huntington,_West_Virginia\", \"score\": 0.7334748790710081, \"rank\": 0.2644960314869742, \"text\": \"Huntington\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Huntington,_West_Virginia\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Huntington,_West_Virginia\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In order to attract buyers, he alsobuilt a trolley systemthat whisked residents from outlying areas to jobs and shopping downtown.\", \"from\": 1462, \"to\": 1592, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"By the 1930s, Los Angeles had a vibrant public transportation network, with over 1,000 miles of electric streetcar routes, operated by two companies:Pacific Electric Railway, with its \\\"Red Cars,\\\" andLos Angeles Railway, with its \\\"Yellow Cars.\\\"\", \"from\": 1594, \"to\": 1837, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1608, \"end\": 1619, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}, {\"begin\": 1743, \"end\": 1767, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pacific_Electric\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Pacific Electric Railway\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pacific_Electric\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Pacific_Electric\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The system wasn't perfect by any means.\", \"from\": 1839, \"to\": 1878, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Many people felt that streetcars were inconvenient and also unhealthy when they were jammed with riders.\", \"from\": 1879, \"to\": 1983, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Moreover, streetcars were slow because they had to share the road with automobiles.\", \"from\": 1984, \"to\": 2067, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"As auto usage climbed and roads became congested, travel times increased.\", \"from\": 2068, \"to\": 2141, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Nonetheless, many Angelenos rode the streetcars-especially during World War II, when gasoline was rationed and automobile plants shifted to producing military vehicles.\", \"from\": 2143, \"to\": 2311, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"In 1910, Los Angeles had a widely used local rail network, with over 1,200 miles (1,930 kilometers) of track.\", \"from\": 2313, \"to\": 2422, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2322, \"end\": 2333, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"What happened?\", \"from\": 2423, \"to\": 2437, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The end of the war marked theend of the line for streetcars.\", \"from\": 2439, \"to\": 2499, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The war effort had transformed oil, tire, and car companies into behemoths, and these industriesneeded new buyersfor goods from the massive factories they had built for military production.\", \"from\": 2500, \"to\": 2689, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Civilians and returning soldiers were tired of rationing and war privations, and they wanted to spend money on goods such as cars.\", \"from\": 2690, \"to\": 2820, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Afteryears of heavy usageduring the war, Los Angeles' streetcar system needed an expensive capital upgrade.\", \"from\": 2822, \"to\": 2929, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2863, \"end\": 2874, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But in the mid-1940s, most of the system was sold to a company called National City Lines, which waspartly owned by the carmaker General Motors, the oil companies Standard Oil of California and Phillips Petroleum, and the Firestone tire company.\", \"from\": 2930, \"to\": 3175, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3000, \"end\": 3019, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/National_City_Lines\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"National City Lines\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/National_City_Lines\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/National_City_Lines\"}, {\"begin\": 3059, \"end\": 3073, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/General_Motors\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 7.00111568174702e-17, \"text\": \"General Motors\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/General_Motors\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/General_Motors\"}, {\"begin\": 3124, \"end\": 3142, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phillips_Petroleum_Company\", \"score\": 0.9999999245665123, \"rank\": 7.543362690845903e-08, \"text\": \"Phillips Petroleum\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phillips_Petroleum_Company\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Phillips_Petroleum_Company\"}, {\"begin\": 3152, \"end\": 3174, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Firestone_Tire_and_Rubber_Company\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Firestone tire company\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Firestone_Tire_and_Rubber_Company\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Firestone_Tire_and_Rubber_Company\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"These powerful forces had no incentive to maintain or improve the old electric streetcar system.\", \"from\": 3177, \"to\": 3273, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"National City ripped up tracks and replaced the streetcars with buses that were built by General Motors, used Firestone tires, and ran on gasoline.\", \"from\": 3274, \"to\": 3421, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3274, \"end\": 3287, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/National_City_Corp.\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.1262761266209825e-31, \"text\": \"National City\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/National_City_Corp.\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/National_City_Corp.\"}, {\"begin\": 3363, \"end\": 3377, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/General_Motors\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 7.00111568174702e-17, \"text\": \"General Motors\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/General_Motors\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/General_Motors\"}, {\"begin\": 3384, \"end\": 3399, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Firestone_Tire_and_Rubber_Company\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Firestone tires\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Firestone_Tire_and_Rubber_Company\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Firestone_Tire_and_Rubber_Company\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"There is a long-running academic debate over whetherself-serving corporate interestspurposelykilled LA's streetcar system.\", \"from\": 3423, \"to\": 3545, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Some researchers argue that the systemwould have died on its own, like manyother streetcar networks around the world.\", \"from\": 3546, \"to\": 3663, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The controversy evenspilled over into pop culturein the 1988 movieWho Framed Roger Rabbit, which came down firmly on the conspiracy side.\", \"from\": 3665, \"to\": 3802, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"What's undisputed is that, starting in the mid-1940s, powerful social forces transformed Los Angeles so that commuters had only two choices: drive or take a public bus.\", \"from\": 3804, \"to\": 3972, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3893, \"end\": 3904, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"As a result, LA became so choked with traffic that it often took hours to cross the city.\", \"from\": 3973, \"to\": 4062, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"In 1990, the Los Angeles Times reported that people wereputting refrigerators, desks, and televisions in their carsto cope with getting stuck in horrendous traffic.\", \"from\": 4064, \"to\": 4228, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4077, \"end\": 4094, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles_Times\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 9.364362785730378e-37, \"text\": \"Los Angeles Times\", \"types\": [\"Q386724\", \"Q234460\", \"Q11032\", \"Q1092563\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles_Times\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles_Times\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"A swath of movies, fromFalling DowntoCluelesstoLa La Land, have featured the next-level challenge of driving in LA.\", \"from\": 4229, \"to\": 4344, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Traffic was also a concern when LA hosted the 1984 Summer Games, but theGames went off smoothly.\", \"from\": 4346, \"to\": 4442, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Organizers convinced over 1 million people to ride buses, and theygot many trucks to drive during off-peakhours.\", \"from\": 4443, \"to\": 4555, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The 2028 games, however,will have roughly 50 percent moreathletes competing, which means thousands more coaches, family, friends, and spectators.\", \"from\": 4556, \"to\": 4701, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"So simply dusting off plans from 40 years ago will not work.\", \"from\": 4702, \"to\": 4762, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Today, Los Angeles is slowly rebuilding a more robust public transportation system.\", \"from\": 4764, \"to\": 4847, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4771, \"end\": 4782, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In addition to buses, it now hasfour light-rail lines-the new name for electric streetcars-and two subways.\", \"from\": 4848, \"to\": 4955, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Many followthe same routes that electric trolleys once traveled.\", \"from\": 4956, \"to\": 5020, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Rebuilding this network iscosting the public billions, since the old system was completely dismantled.\", \"from\": 5021, \"to\": 5123, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Three key improvements are planned for the Olympics.\", \"from\": 5125, \"to\": 5177, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"First, LA's airport terminals will beconnected to the rail system.\", \"from\": 5178, \"to\": 5244, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Second, the Los Angeles organizing committee is planning heavily on using buses to move people.\", \"from\": 5245, \"to\": 5340, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5257, \"end\": 5268, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"It will do this by reassigning some lanes away from cars andmaking them available for 3,000 more buses, which will be borrowed from other locales.\", \"from\": 5341, \"to\": 5487, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Finally, there are plans to permanently increase bicycle lanes around the city.\", \"from\": 5489, \"to\": 5568, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"However, one major initiative,a bike path along the Los Angeles River, is still under an environmental review that may not be completed by 2028.\", \"from\": 5569, \"to\": 5713, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5621, \"end\": 5638, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles_River\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Los Angeles River\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles_River\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles_River\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"I expect thatorganizers will pull off a car-free Olympics, simply by making driving and parking conditions so awful during the Games that people are forced to take public transportation to sports venues around the city.\", \"from\": 5715, \"to\": 5934, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"After the Games end, however, most of LA is likely to quickly revert to its car-centric ways.\", \"from\": 5935, \"to\": 6028, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"AsCasey Wasserman, chair of theLA 2028organizing committee, recently put it: \\\"The unique thing about Olympic Games is for 17 days you can fix a lot of problems when you can set the rules-for traffic, for fans, for commerce-than you do on a normal day in Los Angeles.\\\"\", \"from\": 6030, \"to\": 6297, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6038, \"end\": 6047, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lew_Wasserman\", \"score\": 0.9999998295925397, \"rank\": 1.7040762926657435e-07, \"text\": \"Wasserman\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lew_Wasserman\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Lew_Wasserman\"}, {\"begin\": 6284, \"end\": 6295, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"score\": 0.9992495165633384, \"rank\": 0.0007509828495883192, \"text\": \"Los Angeles\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Los_Angeles\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In your inbox:WIRED'smost ambitious, future-defining stories  Welcome to Big Tech's'Age of Extraction'  Big Interview:Palantir's CEOAlex Karp goes to war  Starlink devices are allegedly being used atscam compounds  Livestream:What businessesneed to know about agentic AI      \\u00a92025Cond\\u00e9 Nast.\", \"from\": 6299, \"to\": 6591, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6417, \"end\": 6425, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Palantir_Technologies\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.4153614136866736e-39, \"text\": \"Palantir\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Palantir_Technologies\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Palantir_Technologies\"}, {\"begin\": 6454, \"end\": 6462, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Starlink\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.639298425355194e-18, \"text\": \"Starlink\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Starlink\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Starlink\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"All rights reserved.WIREDmay earn a portion of sales from products that are purchased through our site as part of our Affiliate Partnerships with retailers.\", \"from\": 6592, \"to\": 6748, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The material on this site may not be reproduced, distributed, transmitted, cached or otherwise used, except with the prior written permission of Cond\\u00e9 Nast.Ad Choices\", \"from\": 6749, \"to\": 6915, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6894, \"end\": 6899, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Louis,_Grand_Cond\\u00e9\", \"score\": 0.7069136048508802, \"rank\": 0.19609582963616856, \"text\": \"Cond\\u00e9\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Louis,_Grand_Cond\\u00e9\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Louis,_Grand_Cond\\u00e9\"}]}]}"